summary:
Andi: Mom, can I ask you something?
Bex: Ask away!
Andi: Silly question, but why don’t you like to go by Rebecca? 
Bex: Because...
body:
Andi: Mom, can I ask you something?

Bex: Ask away!

Andi: Silly question, but why don’t you like to go by Rebecca?

Bex: Because Rebecca sounds like a “Smart girl who stays in school and turns their work in time.” That’s the opposite of me. Bex sounds more cool and fun.

Andi: Oh. Then why does Cece still call you that?

Bex: She probably thinks that if she calls me ‘Rebecca’ I will magically turn into that “perfect school smart” girl she always wanted.

Andi: But that’s me also….

Bex: No it’s not. You’re Andi. Andi Mack. The girl who is smart, but also fun…. so a mix between Rebecca and Bex!

title: Jonah and Libby
body:
Ok, now that I’ve calmed down a bit from the initial wave of joy caused by Libby’s appearance, I actually want to talk about this subplot. I’ve seen a few disappointed that Jonah doesn’t know ASL and only communicates to Libby through texts, myself being one of them. But the more I think about it, the more it makes sense and the more I thought of the potential for an interesting story. 

It’s pretty clear the angle the show is going for with Jonah and Libby’s relationship: how Jonah is still continuing to fail to communicate in his romantic relationships, as he seemingly doesn’t seem concerned with learning ASL which as Andi subtly points out would be more effective and just more meaningful in terms of Jonah and Libby’s relationship. I don’t think this comes from Jonah being lazy, but rather unwilling or simply unable to properly communicate his feelings to someone else in a healthy way. This means that this flaw with Jonah, being unable to express his emotions in healthy manner, will finally be pushed to the forefront of his character since this flaw will be taken to an extreme length with his relationship with Libby. Something to note here is Andi’s interactions with Libby. Notice how she doesn’t seem threatened or insecure around her, but is rather friendly and confident during their conversation. Her comment about Jonah’s method of communication with Libby comes more from a place of genuine concern than wanting to poke holes in their relationship for her own gain. This is great for two reasons: one, it shows how much Andi’s character has matured and developed, and two, it could mean that there’s some actual potential for her and Jonah to end up being friends. Why do I say this? Well, now that Andi seemingly has no romantic interest in Jonah, she can be far more critical of his shortcomings in a constructive manner, no longer blinded by her feelings. This gives me a lot of hope for Jonah’s character, as without the anchor that was Jandi holding him back, we could not only see his character grow in ways unrelated to his relationship to Andi but see Andi interact with Jonah in a healthy, platonic way. I won’t get my hopes up too much, since that’s how I felt back with 2b when it came to Jonah’s subplot, but I’m remaining cautiously optimistic. 

But there’s a whole other part to this story and that’s Libby herself, which many have presumed will be similar to Andi in terms of personality based on their shared interest in crafts, and how Andi could realize this and think about how Jonah has a “type”. I want to be clear before I state this next part because I could see people misinterpreting it: Libby is her own character and I do think she will have some decent if minor development and DO NOT THINK the writers are merely using her as a tool. That being said, I think her purpose in the story will be to highlight Jonah’s failure of communication by taking it into an extreme measure due to her disability, and that once that story is put into motion, she might become irrelevant to story overall. I say this as someone who instantly fell in love with her character and would want nothing more than for Libby to show up in the every episode the rest of the season, but I get the feeling this character’s run will be short-lived, though not necessarily bad. 

Keep in mind, I’m no master of predictions, and there could be some piece of behind the scenes knowledge with scheduling that proves me wrong (I don’t keep up with that sort of thing), and I could be wrong cause it was just a 45 second clip, but everything else this season has seemingly been building up to finally confronting Jonah’s flaws in a meaningful way, starting by Andi finally becoming a friend who can help Jonah without getting hung up on romantic tensions between them.
